Description: A low pressure system approaching Baffin Island will bring gusty easterly winds to the Pangnirtung region tonight and Thursday. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Today's heavy rainfall is the first storm in a week-long series that brings a major pattern change to the province of BC, in particular the south coast. Periods of rain, heavy at times, will continue through Saturday. Embedded thunderstorms and gusty winds are possible. This sudden change to a prolonged wet pattern combined with local gusty winds and trees shedding their leaves may lead to localized flooding. Strong winds may also lead to power outages. Late this week the pattern is intensified once again by a strong low pressure system crossing Vancouver Island Thursday night or Friday. Strong winds, and where they materialize, will depend on the exact storm track. Stay tuned to your local forecast throughout the week as we follow the evolution of this feature. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Periods of heavy rainfall will continue over Howe Sound, Metro Vancouver and the Fraser Valley tonight. This moisture-laden system will deliver 40-70 mm of rain by Thursday morning. Embedded thunderstorms will bring additional localized amounts and rainfall rates of up to 20-30 mm/hr tonight. Rainfall rates will lessen on Thursday but persistent moist, onshore flow will cause showers, heavy at times, to continue. The heaviest rain amounts are expected near the mountains and eastern sections of the Fraser Valley. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Post-tropical Storm Teddy. This is the final statement for this storm. Post-Tropical Storm Teddy continues northeastward into the Strait of Belle Isle and will merge with a larger extratropical low over the Labrador Sea on Thursday. 1. Summary of basic information at 12:30 P.M. NDT. Location: 51.0 north 57.3 west. About 90 kilometers west-southwest of St. Anthony. Maximum sustained winds: 85 kilometers per hour. Present movement: north-northeast at 50 kilometers per hour. Estimated minimum central pressure: 975 millibars. 2. Summary of latest information. Teddy continues to produce strong southerly winds over the western coast of Newfoundland as the centre tracks towards southeastern Labrador. 3 to 5 metres waves are expected to continue over the southern and eastern Atlantic marine waters into Thursday morning. Forecaster(s): McArthur ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
